# yaml-language-server: $schema=https://niro.apxlabs.ai/schema/v1/credentials.json
#
# REFERENCE + INSTRUCTIONS — do not edit, do not delete.
#
# This file is TWO things at once:
#
#   1. The format reference for niro/credentials.yaml.
#   2. The instructions for how to produce niro/credentials.yaml on
#      your machine.
#
# Niro does not scaffold niro/credentials.yaml because it contains
# real secrets. Prefer generating it from the approved `harness/` seed
# mechanism that prepares the application for each run. That mechanism should
# retrieve secrets through your existing secrets workflow and emit the current
# test identities. Manual creation is a fallback for simple environments.
# Niro automatically adds the generated file to .gitignore; keep it local-only.
#
# ---------------------------------------------------------------------
# How to produce niro/credentials.yaml
# ---------------------------------------------------------------------
# Put the chosen pattern in the committed staging preparation or local seed
# mechanism. Niro re-reads the generated file for every run.
#
#   # One-shot heredoc — quick for a single throwaway token
#   cat > niro/credentials.yaml <<'EOF'
#   credentials:
#     - credential_id: TEST_ADMIN
#       description: "test admin account"
#       type: bearer_token
#       secret: "Bearer eyJhbGc..."
#   EOF
#
#   # 1Password CLI
#   op inject -i niro/credentials.template.yaml -o niro/credentials.yaml
#
#   # Doppler
#   doppler run -- ./scripts/render-niro-creds.sh > niro/credentials.yaml
#
#   # AWS Secrets Manager
#   ./scripts/aws-secrets-to-niro-creds.sh > niro/credentials.yaml
#
# Whatever you pick, the GENERATED file is what Niro reads; the preparation or
# generator script is what you commit. Keep credentials.yaml local-only.
#
# ---------------------------------------------------------------------
# IMPORTANT: keep environments in SEPARATE Niro configs
# ---------------------------------------------------------------------
# Don't mix throwaway test creds with production audit tokens in one
# file. Niro picks creds by credential_id and description — if a prod admin
# token is sitting in this catalog, Niro can grab it by mistake
# during a "staging" run. Each Niro config has its own credentials
# catalog; isolation is by directory, not by naming convention. For
# multiple environments, scaffold a separate niro/ directory per env
# (e.g., niro/, niro-staging/, niro-prod/), each with its own
# credentials.yaml.
#
# ---------------------------------------------------------------------
# Why you need ≥2 users per role
# ---------------------------------------------------------------------
# The most common real API bugs are authorization bugs — the kind
# where logged-in users reach data or actions they shouldn't. Niro
# can only find these if it can compare what different users are
# allowed to do.
#
# Two axes of escalation Niro tests for:
#
#   * Horizontal escalation — same role, different identity.
#     Example: User A logs in and tries to read User B's orders. If
#     the response succeeds, that's a bug ("any logged-in user can
#     read any other user's orders"). To test this, Niro needs creds
#     for BOTH User A and User B. With only one user, Niro can only
#     verify "I can read my own resources" — which is correct
#     behavior, not a bug.
#
#   * Vertical escalation — lower role, higher surface.
#     Example: a standard user logs in and tries to hit an admin-only
#     endpoint. If the response succeeds, that's a bug ("non-admins
#     can do admin things"). To test this, Niro needs both a standard
#     user AND an admin, so it can verify the standard user is denied
#     at admin endpoints.
#
# Minimum cred set for full coverage:
#
#   * 2 standard users (User A, User B). Each must OWN DIFFERENT
#     resources (orders, projects, files, organizations). If both
#     users own the same resources, "User A can read X" is correct
#     and proves nothing.
#   * ≥1 admin user. Niro pairs the admin with each standard user
#     to verify admin-only surfaces are properly gated.
#   * 2 admins if your app has org-scoped admins (an admin in Org X
#     should not see Org Y's data). Skip if a single global admin
#     covers everything.
#
# Per-app expansion: most B2B SaaS has more roles (Manager, Editor,
# Owner, Member). Add 2 creds at each role you care about — same
# pattern.
#
# ---------------------------------------------------------------------
# A principal's effective privilege is NOT its role name
# ---------------------------------------------------------------------
# Role is only one axis of identity. Apps also grant capabilities that
# cut ACROSS roles — instance/server-admin flags (isSuperAdmin,
# canImpersonate, canAccessAdminPanel), feature entitlements, group
# memberships, or elevated per-object grants a nominally-low role
# happens to hold. Derive each principal's REAL permissions from the
# app's authorization code / seed / DB and state them in the
# description; do not trust the role label alone.
#
# This is what separates a real finding from a false one. If a "Guest"
# also holds, say, canImpersonate and the description omits it, Niro
# correctly sees that Guest impersonating — and WRONGLY reports a
# privilege escalation. The capability was legitimately held; only the
# missing context made it look like a bug. So each description must make
# the principal's TRUE reachable surface explicit: its role, the
# resources it owns, AND any capability a reader could not infer from
# the role name.
#
# (Same coin, flip side — see the section above: too few principals or
# shared ownership and Niro can't compare users at all, so real bugs go
# unseen. Accurate identity context is what makes both directions work.)
#
# Generating this file with an agent? Read the authorization code and
# seed/DB to record each principal's real effective permissions, and
# reconcile the nominal role with the actual flags before writing the
# description.
#
# ---------------------------------------------------------------------
# Schema (intentionally minimal)
# ---------------------------------------------------------------------
# Every entry has one stable ID plus the fields required by its auth type:
#
#   credential_id — required customer-defined ID for this credential.
#                   Must be unique in this file and match
#                   ^[A-Z][A-Z0-9_]{0,63}$.
#                   Keep this ID stable when rotating values or editing
#                   the description. Niro uses it in reports and as the
#                   bash env-var prefix: <CREDENTIAL_ID>_<FIELD_NAME>.
#
#   identifier  — value the auth system uses to identify the
#                 principal: username, email, employee id, OAuth
#                 client_id, service account name, anything. Whatever
#                 the auth call's actual form-field name is (email,
#                 username, login, principal, sub, etc.) Niro
#                 figures out from the description + your app's
#                 source — it doesn't presume a mapping.
#                 Required for username_password.
#                 Rejected for bearer_token / static_token (their
#                 tokens are self-identifying).
#
#   secret      — value the principal presents to authenticate:
#                 password, bearer token, static API key, HMAC
#                 signing key, anything that proves identity.
#                 Required for username_password, bearer_token,
#                 static_token, and signing algorithms prefixed
#                 with hmac-.
#                 Read literally — Niro does NOT perform env-var
#                 expansion. Put the real value here; rely on the
#                 .gitignore + your local file-system permissions to
#                 keep it private.
#
# Anything beyond identifier + secret that the auth call needs
# (organization, tenant, application id, custom request headers, MFA
# bypass, expected response shape) goes in `description`. Keep
# description complete — Niro reads it at credential-pick time
# AND uses it to construct the actual login call. Under-specified
# descriptions cause failed logins or credentials being used for the
# wrong tests. Each description is capped at 1000 characters (counted in
# runes); offload bulky reference data (IDs, endpoints) to fixtures.yaml.
#
# Supported types:
#
#   username_password — required: identifier, secret
#   bearer_token      — required: secret
#   static_token      — required: secret. Tell Niro where to
#                       send it (header:NAME / cookie:NAME /
#                       query:NAME) in description.
#   signing           — required: algorithm.
#                       algorithm is free-form. Values prefixed with
#                       hmac- require secret and expose it to bash as
#                       $<CREDENTIAL_ID>_SECRET. All other algorithms
#                       require key_pem and expose a private-key file
#                       path as $<CREDENTIAL_ID>_KEY_PEM_FILE.
#                       Niro sees only these handles, never the
#                       raw HMAC secret or private key bytes. Put the
#                       exact request-signing scheme in description:
#                       header name, hex/base64 encoding, raw body vs
#                       canonical string, timestamp format, target
#                       root URL, and any prefix like `sha256=`.
#                       Keep description concise: it is capped at 1000
#                       characters. credential_id, not description, is
#                       the stable refresh key.
#                       key_pem must be an unencrypted private key.
#                       Decrypt locally with:
#                         openssl pkey -in encrypted.key -out plaintext.key
#   mtls              — required: cert_pem, key_pem.
#                       optional: ca_pem (needed when the target uses
#                       a private CA). At runtime Niro writes
#                       PEM files to disk and exposes them as path
#                       env vars: $<CREDENTIAL_ID>_CERT_PEM_FILE,
#                       $<CREDENTIAL_ID>_KEY_PEM_FILE, and
#                       $<CREDENTIAL_ID>_CA_PEM_FILE. For example:
#                         curl --cert $PARTNER_MTLS_CERT_PEM_FILE \
#                              --key  $PARTNER_MTLS_KEY_PEM_FILE  \
#                              --cacert $PARTNER_MTLS_CA_PEM_FILE \
#                              https://partner-api.example.com/
#                       cert_pem must not be expired; key_pem must not
#                       be passphrase-protected (decrypt with openssl
#                       pkey -in encrypted.key -out plaintext.key).
#
# ---------------------------------------------------------------------
# Worked example — the shape your generated credentials.yaml should
# take. Copy the structure; fill with your real values via your
# generation script.
# ---------------------------------------------------------------------
credentials:
  # --- Standard users: paired for horizontal-escalation testing ---
  # Description includes role + ownership + auth-call context (login
  # path, body shape) + pairing intent + any capability that does NOT
  # follow from the role name (admin flags, entitlements). That is the
  # level Niro needs to log in, pick the cred for the right tests, and
  # not misread a held permission as escalation.
  - credential_id: STANDARD_USER_A
    description: "Standard user A. Owns orders, projects, and uploads
      in Org A. Login: POST /api/login with body {email, password}.
      Pair with Standard User B for horizontal-escalation tests:
      authenticate as A, attempt to read/modify B's resources, expect
      403."
    type: username_password
    identifier: user-a@example.test
    secret: <user-a-password>

  - credential_id: STANDARD_USER_B
    description: "Standard user B. Owns orders, projects, and uploads
      in Org B. Login: same shape as User A. Different resources from
      User A so cross-user access attempts have something to fail at."
    type: username_password
    identifier: user-b@example.test
    secret: <user-b-password>

  # --- Admin: paired with standard users for vertical-escalation testing ---
  # Note: identifier is a username (not an email) — the schema accepts
  # whatever value the auth system actually identifies the principal by.
  - credential_id: GLOBAL_ADMIN
    description: "Global admin. Login: POST /api/login with body
      {username, password, organization='built-in'}. Standard users
      above must NOT reach admin-only surfaces (/admin/*, user
      management, billing, audit logs); Niro authenticates as a
      standard user and verifies admin endpoints reject the request."
    type: username_password
    identifier: admin
    secret: <admin-password>

  # --- Low role that ALSO holds a cross-cutting capability ---
  # The "effective privilege != role name" rule, made concrete: role
  # Guest, but it also holds an instance-wide canImpersonate flag (on
  # the user record, independent of role). State that explicitly — else
  # Niro sees a "Guest" impersonating and reports a FALSE escalation,
  # when the capability is legitimately held.
  - credential_id: GUEST_WITH_IMPERSONATE
    description: "Role: Guest in Org A (read-only on most objects). ALSO
      holds an instance-wide canImpersonate flag (on the user record,
      independent of role), so impersonating within Org A is BY DESIGN,
      not escalation. Login: POST /api/login with body {email, password}.
      Use to verify Guest object-level limits AND to distinguish
      legitimate impersonation from a real escalation."
    type: username_password
    identifier: guest-with-impersonate@example.test
    secret: <password>

  # --- Service-to-service bearer token ---
  # bearer_token has no identifier — the token IS the identity.
  - credential_id: WEBHOOK_SERVICE
    description: "Service-to-service bearer token used by the webhook
      integration. Sent as `Authorization: Bearer <token>`. Surface is
      different from human-user paths — Niro probes whether the
      human-bearer and service-bearer code paths have the right
      authorization gating between them (a bug class where service
      tokens silently inherit god-mode is common)."
    type: bearer_token
    secret: "Bearer <service-token>"

  # --- API key: shows static_token shape + placement-in-description ---
  - credential_id: PUBLIC_API_CUSTOMER
    description: "Per-customer API key for the public API. Send as the
      `X-API-Key` request header (header:X-API-Key — that's how Niro
      learns where to put the value). If your app issues API keys per
      customer, add 2 keys here (one per fictional customer) so Niro
      can test cross-customer access on this auth surface too."
    type: static_token
    secret: <api-key>

  # --- Payload signing (HMAC or private-key request signatures) ---
  # Use when the target rejects unsigned requests. The signing secret
  # or private key never enters Niro's reasoning: list_credentials shows
  # only the handle ($WEBHOOK_SIGNER_SECRET or
  # $PARTNER_API_SIGNER_KEY_PEM_FILE), and bash
  # receives the actual material when it runs openssl/curl. Niro does
  # not compute signatures; Niro uses the description + app source
  # to construct the signed request.
  #
  # The description is load-bearing. Keep it short, but include the
  # exact scheme: what bytes get signed, output encoding, signature
  # header, timestamp header/format if any, and prefixes like
  # `sha256=`. Keep credential_id stable when the description changes.
  #
  # HMAC-SHA256 shared-secret signer:
  #
  # - credential_id: WEBHOOK_SIGNER
  #   description: "Webhook signer for https://api.example.com/. HMAC-SHA256 over raw body, base64, send as X-Signature."
  #   type: signing
  #   algorithm: hmac-sha256
  #   secret: <shared-hmac-key>
  #
  # Private-key signer:
  #
  # Any non-hmac- algorithm uses key_pem. key_pem must contain a real
  # unencrypted private key (RSA, EC, Ed25519, or another Go-supported
  # private key). Placeholder PEM blocks fail at load time, so this
  # example stays commented out.
  #
  # - credential_id: PARTNER_API_SIGNER
  #   description: "Partner API signer. RSA-SHA256 over timestamp+newline+body, base64, send Signature and Timestamp headers."
  #   type: signing
  #   algorithm: rsa-sha256
  #   key_pem: |
  #     -----BEGIN PRIVATE KEY-----
  #     <paste your unencrypted RSA private key here>
  #     -----END PRIVATE KEY-----
  #
  # ECDSA private-key signer:
  #
  # - credential_id: DEVICE_API_SIGNER
  #   description: "Device API signer for https://iot.example.com/. ECDSA-P256-SHA256 over raw body, base64 DER signature, send as X-Sig."
  #   type: signing
  #   algorithm: ecdsa-sha256
  #   key_pem: |
  #     -----BEGIN EC PRIVATE KEY-----
  #     <paste your unencrypted EC private key here>
  #     -----END EC PRIVATE KEY-----

  # --- mTLS (mutual TLS client certificate) ---
  # Use when the target API requires a client certificate for
  # authentication. Niro writes the PEM files to disk and passes
  # the paths to bash via $PARTNER_MTLS_CERT_PEM_FILE /
  # $PARTNER_MTLS_KEY_PEM_FILE / $PARTNER_MTLS_CA_PEM_FILE so curl can
  # use them with --cert / --key / --cacert.
  #
  # Generate the PEM values from your existing cert/key files:
  #   cert_pem: "$(cat client.crt)"
  #   key_pem:  "$(cat client.key)"      # must NOT be passphrase-protected
  #   ca_pem:   "$(cat ca-chain.crt)"    # omit for public-CA-signed certs
  #
  # ca_pem accepts a PEM bundle — concatenate intermediate and root CA
  # certificates to support full chain verification:
  #   cat intermediate.crt root.crt > ca-chain.crt
  #
  # If your key is encrypted, decrypt it first:
  #   openssl pkey -in encrypted.key -out client.key
  #
  # The description should name the partner / service and note the
  # endpoint root so Niro knows when to pick this cred.
  # Unlike the other credential types above, the mTLS entry cannot use
  # placeholder values — cert_pem and key_pem must contain real PEM
  # content because Niro validates them at load time (PEM parse, x509
  # parse, expiry check, cert/key match). Copy the structure below;
  # replace the PEM blocks with your actual cert and key material.
  #
  # - credential_id: PARTNER_MTLS
  #   description: "Partner API client certificate for https://partner-api.example.com/.
  #     All /v2/* endpoints require mutual TLS; use this cert to authenticate.
  #     Recipe: curl --cert $PARTNER_MTLS_CERT_PEM_FILE --key $PARTNER_MTLS_KEY_PEM_FILE
  #     --cacert $PARTNER_MTLS_CA_PEM_FILE https://partner-api.example.com/v2/status"
  #   type: mtls
  #   cert_pem: |
  #     -----BEGIN CERTIFICATE-----
  #     <paste your client certificate here>
  #     -----END CERTIFICATE-----
  #   key_pem: |
  #     -----BEGIN PRIVATE KEY-----
  #     <paste your unencrypted private key here>
  #     -----END PRIVATE KEY-----
  #   # ca_pem is optional — include when the target uses a private CA:
  #   # ca_pem: |
  #   #   -----BEGIN CERTIFICATE-----
  #   #   <paste your CA certificate here>
  #   #   -----END CERTIFICATE-----
